>> title: Sheet-Pan Chicken Breast
>> cuisine: American
>> tags: protein, poultry, high-protein, gluten-free, soy-free, batch-prep
>> servings: 5
>> yield: 5 portions
>> storage_days: 4
>> storage_method: refrigerated
>> reheat: Gently in a covered skillet with a splash of water, or microwave 60-90 seconds. Don't overheat or it dries out.

-- Novice goal: cook chicken breast to temperature WITHOUT drying it out.
-- The whole trick is a thermometer and a rest. Pull it at 160F; it climbs to a safe 165F while resting.

Heat #oven{} to 425F (220C). Line a #sheet pan{} with parchment.

Pat @chicken breasts{2%lbs}(about 4) completely dry with a paper towel -- dry meat browns, wet meat steams.

If a breast is much thicker on one end, lay it under plastic wrap and gently pound the thick part until the whole piece is an even thickness. Even thickness cooks evenly.

Rub all over with @olive oil{2%tbsp}, then season both sides with @kosher salt{2%tsp}, @black pepper{1%tsp}, @garlic powder{1%tsp}, and @smoked paprika{1%tsp}.

Roast ~{18-22%minutes}, until an instant-read #thermometer{} pushed into the thickest part reads 160F (71C). Start checking at 18 minutes -- ovens vary.

Rest the chicken ~{5%minutes} before slicing. This is not optional: cutting early spills the juices, resting keeps them in, and the temperature carries up to a safe 165F during the rest.

Slice across the grain (perpendicular to the visible muscle lines) for the most tender bite.

-- Used in: sheet-pan chicken bowls, wraps, salads, grain bowls
